00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:53.740
With a Doctorate in Zoology
from the University of Florida,

00:01:53.740 --> 00:01:56.550
Kay is a Professor of Biology

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:59.310
at Gettysburg College
in Pennsylvania.

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.470
She teaches courses in Biology,

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:05.110
Comparative Physiology,
and Ecology.

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:09.260
Her research and publications
have ranged from hibernation

00:02:09.260 --> 00:02:13.010
in lizards, estivation
in salamanders,

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:16.990
and the foraging behavior
of tropical bat species.

00:02:16.990 --> 00:02:21.420
Beginning at least 10 years
ago, probably a bit longer,

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:26.630
with her publication
of <i>Loathsome Beasts,</i>

00:02:26.630 --> 00:02:32.920
<i>Images of Reptiles and
Amphibians in Art and Science </i>,

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:37.570
she has been a strong
proponent of the expansion

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:40.940
of STEM education to STEAM,

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:45.510
incorporating the arts
with the sciences.

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:49.280
[ Laughter and Applause ]

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:53.300
Her focus on the role of
images in plants and animals

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.860
in the history of the
natural sciences led

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:59.950
to her being a driving force
in organizing and speaking

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:04.830
at the International Conference
on the 17th century naturalist

00:03:04.830 --> 00:03:08.480
and artist, Maria Sibylla
Merian at the University

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:13.190
of Amsterdam last summer which
I was lucky enough to attend.

00:03:13.190 --> 00:03:16.690
Her talk today will be just
as interesting I'm sure --

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:19.260
Art and Science Intertwined.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:23.510
Please join me in welcoming
Professor Kay Etheridge.

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:33.040
[ Applause ]

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:34.340
&gt;&gt; Kay Etheridge: Thank
you, Leslie, and thank you

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:36.020
to the organizers of this event.

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:40.240
It's just something I'm
really enjoying very much.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:44.610
So to get started here I've
already changed my talk

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:48.950
with notes from this morning,
so we'll see how this works in.

00:03:48.950 --> 00:03:53.890
But some points were made that
I'd like to link to my own talk

00:03:53.890 --> 00:03:55.190
because it's thoughts I've had,

00:03:55.190 --> 00:03:56.580
and I think they'll
link very nicely now

00:03:56.580 --> 00:03:58.060
that we're back on Earth.

00:03:58.060 --> 00:04:03.380
So I'm going to start
talking about nature images

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.310
with this very sophisticated
one.

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:09.950
This is going to be -- this
is going to be Biology.

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.960
I'll just say there's
obviously many kinds

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.730
of nature, but this is Biology.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:15.650
So I'm going to make
the argument --

00:04:15.650 --> 00:04:18.660
I'm going to talk about the
purposes of these nature images,

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:20.170
meaning Biology images.

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:22.690
What purposes can
they serve aside

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:24.410
from being aesthetically
beautiful

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:27.580
and stimulating and inspiring?

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:30.470
You can -- they can
be decorative,

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:34.670
they can be symbolic,
they certainly can be used

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:37.370
to influence, you know,
don't smoke in the forest

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:38.670
and drop your cigarettes.

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:42.370
And I'm going to concentrate
on the information in images

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:46.960
because as a biologist that's
one way I look at images,

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:49.250
is what information is there?

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:51.060
And how is this information
presented?

00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:53.830
And since I was a child
I liked creepy crawlers,

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:55.600
hence the snakes
and bats and such.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:57.990
And I'll get back
to this image later.

00:04:57.990 --> 00:04:59.500
But there's a tremendous amount

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:02.470
of information packed
into this image.

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:07.920
There's also the perspective
of the viewer which we heard

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:10.980
about this morning to
take into consideration.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.060
And here you have your
face-up close in a slice

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:17.590
of tropical life in
what's going on here.

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:25.210
So a little bit about how nature
images have changed over time.

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:30.280
And I'm going to zip through
many millennia very quickly

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:31.580
on that.

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:33.690
And then slow down as we
get to the Renaissance.

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:35.600
And how have these
images been spread?

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:36.960
How have they been disseminated?

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:38.360
There's a couple
of different way.

00:05:38.360 --> 00:05:40.060
We'll talk about that.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.660
And the last thing, and the
most important in a way,

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:46.950
is why are these portrayals
of nature important?

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:49.630
And the biggest point
I want to make is

00:05:49.630 --> 00:05:52.170
that they affect how we
understand and how we think

00:05:52.170 --> 00:05:53.820
about the natural world.

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:56.540
And I think there was
some of this also brought

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:58.800
into the talks this morning,
but we're just looking at it

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.110
on a different level now.

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:02.930
So, I'm going to
use a case study

00:06:02.930 --> 00:06:07.880
on my favorite naturalist
artist, Maria Sibylla Merian,

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:10.300
and that's too immersed in now

00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:12.960
because I'm writing
a book on her.

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:14.950
And so there will be
a lot of her images.

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:17.410
And this is one of
her images as well.

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:20.460
So we're going to go
back 20,000 years.

00:06:20.460 --> 00:06:22.380
No, more than that,
because this is B.C., right?

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:26.230
So nature images have
been around a long time,

00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:27.530
longer than this even.

00:06:27.530 --> 00:06:29.530
So, clearly they're important.

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:34.500
You don't go into a cave
with a torch, with materials

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:36.770
that you've made yourself,
and pigments that you've dug

00:06:36.770 --> 00:06:40.290
up from the Earth, and somehow
go up high and make these images

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:43.400
of these animals unless
it's important to you.

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:46.490
Why this was important
enough to do, I don't know.

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:48.770
This is not something I work on.

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:50.630
But it's early nature images.

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:56.360
Moving forward many millennia,
you've got frescoes in Greece.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:58.770
And these are somewhat
naturalistic.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:01.330
You can tell there
are dolphin and fish.

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:03.430
I don't know what the
purposes of these were.

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:04.730
They may have been symbolic.

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:06.460
But they're also showing
what was around them.

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:08.810
There's water all
around and there's fish.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:11.870
And the fish are important
to their livelihood.

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:14.640
So these images continue.

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:17.210
This is a fairly
naturalistic lion except

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:23.430
for the problem that, if that's
an adult male he would be taller

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:26.120
than that man on his hind legs.

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:27.960
So here symbolism is important.

00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:31.950
This is a king, and the king
can't be smaller than the lion.

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:34.060
The king can't look afraid
in front of the lion.

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.570
So even though you've
got a naturalistic image,

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:38.800
it's not about the lion.

00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:41.710
It's not about what a lion
looks like or what a lion does.

00:07:41.710 --> 00:07:44.450
It's about the king's power.

00:07:44.450 --> 00:07:47.200
So this is maybe decorative.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:48.500
I don't know.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:51.860
I took this photograph
in the museum in Naples,

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:54.750
but this would have been
on the floor in Pompei.

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:57.950
And it's in pretty good
shape because it was buried

00:07:57.950 --> 00:07:59.890
for a long time by Vesuvius.

00:07:59.890 --> 00:08:04.310
And then they excavated it and
looked at these mosaics closely.

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:06.950
Each little piece is about
the size of maybe one

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:10.660
of your fingernails,
and they portray fairly

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:12.570
naturalistic organisms.

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:16.240
You can easily tell that's
a squid and a dogfish

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:18.730
and an ichthyologist could
probably identify a lot

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:20.410
of these fish to species.

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:22.660
There's enough information there

00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:26.780
to tell you what kind
of fish this was.

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:30.350
Nature images continue on in the
medieval times in many forms.

00:08:30.350 --> 00:08:33.800
And in some ways, less
naturalistic than things

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:35.100
that proceeded them in Europe.

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:40.690
And I just put up three
kinds of books, nature books.

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:43.900
These wouldn't have been
printed books, but handwritten

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.780
and hand-illustrated
before the printing press.

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:49.320
And I always -- when I show
this, I ask my students

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:53.570
if they know what kind of
plant that is in that herbal.

00:08:53.570 --> 00:08:55.530
These were used for medical.

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:56.830
&gt;&gt; Mandrake, mandrake.

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:58.130
&gt;&gt; Kay Etheridge: Right.

00:08:58.130 --> 00:08:59.430
And what do you think --
if I say Harry Potter,

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:00.730
how fast do you think
they'd get that?

00:09:00.730 --> 00:09:02.490
Yeah. So, this mandrake.

00:09:02.490 --> 00:09:04.530
They look at the Greek and
Latin, and they don't make --

00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:05.830
get Mandrake out of it.

00:09:05.830 --> 00:09:08.220
But they've read <i>Harry
Potter </i>or seen the movies.

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:11.270
So herbals conveyed information.

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:14.740
And the idea would be to -- if
it was an illustrated herbal,

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:17.420
would be to give you
enough information

00:09:17.420 --> 00:09:20.320
that you would choose the
right plant for a medicine.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:21.620
And some of the herbals --

00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:26.370
it's pretty hard to
tell what the plant is.

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:29.300
Bestiaries are another
thing altogether.

00:09:29.300 --> 00:09:32.620
Bestiaries would
have varying degrees

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:35.610
of naturalistic representation
of animals,

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:37.040
but that wasn't the point.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:39.470
The point was to make
-- to tell the stories,

00:09:39.470 --> 00:09:42.100
to have an allegory, to
have a moral, often related

00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:43.920
to the Bible, although a lot

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:46.100
of these stories were
much older than the Bible.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.400
This is a gorgeous example
that's in the University

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:50.070
of Aberdeen, and it's online.

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:52.180
You could see images
through the whole thing.

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:54.430
So this is about 1200.

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:57.080
And what is that animal?

00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:58.380
I can't see that.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:09:59.680
The slide is blinding.

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:00.980
What is that animal?

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:02.280
There's lots of them.

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:03.580
What are those?

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:04.880
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation:
They're snakes.

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:06.180
&gt;&gt; Kay Etheridge:
They're snakes, right?

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:07.480
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:08.780
&gt;&gt; Kay Etheridge: Okay.

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:10.270
Snakes arrive coming
out of the fire.

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:12.250
These are salamanders.

00:10:12.250 --> 00:10:15.220
So they look nothing like what
we think of as the salamander.

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:18.430
But the Latin text with
this says salamander.

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.660
And the salamanders are
poisoning the apples

00:10:20.660 --> 00:10:22.490
and poisoning the water.

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:24.130
So there's information here.

00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:27.060
Salamanders are poisonous
and they survive fire.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:28.480
There's not very
good information

00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:30.630
about what a salamander
looks like, but the monk

00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:33.930
who illustrated this probably
didn't know what a salamander

00:10:33.930 --> 00:10:35.410
was or what it looked like.

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:39.060
So hold that image and hold
the idea of fire and poison

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:41.680
and salamanders, and
we'll come back to that.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:43.290
Okay. So in hunting [inaudible].

00:10:43.290 --> 00:10:44.590
These are beautiful.

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:45.890
They're decorative.

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:47.190
But there's information
about how

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:48.490
to find things you want to hunt.

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:50.630
So these kinds of images
through the medieval period.

00:10:50.630 --> 00:10:57.010
And then, if I can
go forward here,

00:10:57.010 --> 00:10:59.590
in the Renaissance
the rebirth --

00:10:59.590 --> 00:11:02.810
there is a move towards
more naturalism.

00:11:02.810 --> 00:11:05.780
And Leonardo de Vinci's sort
of the post child for that,

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:07.850
and Albrecht Durer's
another one.

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:10.880
And this is the Little
Tuft of Grass of Piece

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:12.180
of Turf I think is the title.

00:11:12.180 --> 00:11:14.420
And it's about -- I'd
say it's about that big.

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:15.780
It's a tiny painting.

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:17.900
I've only see it once in person.

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:21.590
And it's got beautifully
rendered --

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:23.500
see the dandelion here?

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:25.940
You can tell exactly
what that is.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:28.960
And then he did animals
and this bunny.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:32.460
You feel like you could touch
his fur, and it would be soft.

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:37.380
And this is what he thought
a rhinoceros looked like.

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:39.950
So this is not Durer's fault.

00:11:39.950 --> 00:11:43.690
If he had even seen a rhinoceros
it would probably be a more

00:11:43.690 --> 00:11:44.990
naturalistic rendering.

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:46.290
But he did not see one.

00:11:46.290 --> 00:11:47.640
At least we don't think he did.

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:51.550
And he based this
incredibly long-living image

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:54.000
of a rhinoceros on
notes from someone else,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.300
maybe sketches from
someone else.

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:57.900
I don't actually
recall the whole story.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:00.310
But this image gets
reprinted all the way

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:05.380
up into 19th century German
textbooks as being a rhinoceros.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:10.020
So this dissemination of
images changes dramatically

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:12.780
with the advent of
the printing press.

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:17.030
It then becomes easy to make
images very quickly relative

00:12:17.030 --> 00:12:19.730
to hand-copying each one.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.030
It also makes them
less expensive.

00:12:22.030 --> 00:12:25.180
They're still expensive
to the average person,

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:26.730
but they're much less expensive

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:28.180
than if they're hand-made
images.

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:30.410
So images are spreading faster.

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:32.500
They're not always
spreading accurate

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:35.870
or naturalistic information, but
they're moving around faster.

00:12:35.870 --> 00:12:42.570
So here's 16th century herbal
on the right, a page from one.

00:12:42.570 --> 00:12:46.640
And I wanted to also bring
out the point about color.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:51.390
So some of the information in
images is color, and Leslie

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:53.650
and I were just talking
about this at lunch.

00:12:53.650 --> 00:12:55.580
We were talking about this
at lunch because later

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:58.670
on naturalists actually
used guides

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:00.730
as to how to describe color.

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:02.650
But if you bought a
book in these days,

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:05.900
you usually bought it, or print,
you usually bought it uncolored.

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:09.440
To buy a colored copy
would cost much, much more.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:11.360
And so people would
color them themselves.

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:15.790
So the books you see now in the
Library, in Leslie's library,

00:13:15.790 --> 00:13:19.370
that are colored, changes
are pretty good they were not

00:13:19.370 --> 00:13:21.800
colored by the person who
actually produced the book.

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:23.720
But they were colored later.

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:27.250
And that -- the quality of
coloring, the way it's put on,

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:31.940
whether the colors are natural
or not, varies tremendously.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:35.420
So colored printing is not
coming along for hundreds --

00:13:35.420 --> 00:13:37.640
for a long time after my talk.

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:42.010
So everything you see
will be hand-colored.

00:13:42.010 --> 00:13:43.310
All right.

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:47.170
So in terms of dissemination
of both information and images,

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:51.090
at the same time you've got the
printing press revolutionizing

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:52.390
how images are made.

00:13:52.390 --> 00:13:55.380
You've got people,
Europeans, travelling the globe

00:13:55.380 --> 00:13:58.380
and collecting things.

00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:00.940
Now if you think that
all of the animals

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:05.300
on the planet are what you've
read about in the Bible or seen

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:08.280
in a bestiary, you're
going to be surprised

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:12.730
when you see an armadillo or
a giraffe or a hippopotamus

00:14:12.730 --> 00:14:14.370
or a crocodile in these things

00:14:14.370 --> 00:14:17.950
that start coming back
all over the world.

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:20.970
You're going to see a banana.

00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:22.270
Imagine a banana.

00:14:22.270 --> 00:14:26.670
And this stuff is coming back
and people are collecting it,

00:14:26.670 --> 00:14:30.020
and collecting is even quite
a competitive sport among the

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:31.530
people who can afford it.

00:14:31.530 --> 00:14:34.840
So people make collection
cabinets,

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:38.160
and a cabinet can be anything
literally from a small cabinet

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:42.290
to a suite of rooms if you --
or prints, and can afford it.

00:14:42.290 --> 00:14:45.600
And this one is one of
my favorites in part just

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:49.280
because it does name
Old Worm, Ole Worm.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.100
But he was a Danish Physician,

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:55.560
and this is from a book he had
published about his cabinet.

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.990
So they'd make the collection
and they'd publish about it,

00:14:57.990 --> 00:15:00.330
so you've got images
of the collection.

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:01.630
And you can't see it very well,

00:15:01.630 --> 00:15:06.280
but mixed in with baby stuffed
polar bears and naturalia,

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:09.380
or excuse me, artifacts
from humans like kayaks,

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:11.320
are little art objects,

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:14.700
like there's a little
Giambologna statuette

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:16.000
over there.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.830
And he also had animals, alive.

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:26.370
This is the only known image
made from life of a Great Auk.

00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:28.310
They've been extinct
for quite a while.

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:29.990
This was his pet.

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:32.360
And I guess he probably
stuffed it when it died.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:33.660
But he illustrated it.

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:34.960
He had it illustrated .

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:36.830
As far as I know he did not
make his own illustrations.

00:15:36.830 --> 00:15:42.170
So these images -- then
people can see what an auk is

00:15:42.170 --> 00:15:43.610
and they can name it
and they can think

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:47.120
about its place in
the natural world.

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:50.150
So this brings us
to other travelers.

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:51.760
I like this guy, Pierre Belon.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.890
He would include
like fish recipes

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:55.680
in his book on great stuff.

00:15:55.680 --> 00:15:57.080
He was French after all.

00:15:57.080 --> 00:15:58.740
But here's this giraffe.

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:01.640
I believe he made his
own images in woodcuts.

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:02.940
And here's this chameleon.

00:16:02.940 --> 00:16:06.890
This chameleon's going to
pop up again later, too.

00:16:06.890 --> 00:16:09.270
And he travelled extensively.

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:12.490
I'm just putting in
here, as an example.

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:15.900
And people who travelled
brought things back.

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:17.680
And other people
collected these things.

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:22.820
And this was a collection in
Naples made by an apothecary,

00:16:22.820 --> 00:16:29.450
Ferrante, Imperato, and it was
visited by people from all over.

00:16:29.450 --> 00:16:32.590
So a part of the grand
tour of a young gentleman

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:36.260
or scholar would be to go and
visit these collection cabinets.

00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:39.200
And then these people made
images of their collections.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:40.580
They published these in books.

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:41.880
There's a whole book
of his collection.

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:44.510
They brought their little dogs.

00:16:44.510 --> 00:16:46.250
But what I want to
focus in on is

00:16:46.250 --> 00:16:51.180
in these collections there
are also books and prints.

00:16:51.180 --> 00:16:54.620
So the collection is
artifacts and objects,

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:57.140
books and prints as well.

00:16:57.140 --> 00:17:00.750
And I've been really lucky
twice to teach a course

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:03.050
at Gettysburg College
to undergraduates

00:17:03.050 --> 00:17:05.480
where the students made
a collection cabinet

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:06.930
in the art gallery.

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:08.280
And this was in 2012.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:10.990
I team-taught it with
Felicia Else, my colleague

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:13.210
in Renaissance Art History.

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:18.760
And the students assembled this,
and these are facsimilie books.

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:20.800
I don't want you
librarians to worry

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:25.300
that we have actual Aldrovandi's
line out for everyone to fondle.

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:32.190
And then this was the one
last fall, and narwhal tusk.

00:17:32.190 --> 00:17:38.940
This is to show we have Catesby
prints and then we have a gar

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:40.960
to go with Catesby's gar.

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:44.430
This was the students' idea to
put these pairings together.

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:48.390
And we've got the crocodile
and the alligator skulls.

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:51.310
So the point is these
collections --

00:17:51.310 --> 00:17:54.130
it was just as important for
them to have images as it was

00:17:54.130 --> 00:17:55.560
for them to have the artifacts.

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:57.170
And then if you visited
a collection,

00:17:57.170 --> 00:18:00.170
you might make an image and then
share that with your friends.

00:18:00.170 --> 00:18:02.370
Or you might document
your collection

00:18:02.370 --> 00:18:04.030
by publishing a book on it.

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.340
So the physical object,
the artifact,

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:10.400
and the images were
very much interwoven.

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:15.830
So here's a painting to
Jacopo Ligozzi who worked

00:18:15.830 --> 00:18:20.560
for the Medici and was sort of
loaned out by them, I think,

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:23.560
to Aldrovandi when he
made his encyclopedia.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:26.290
Now I want you just to
compare the information

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:28.590
in these two things.

00:18:31.060 --> 00:18:33.190
I scaled it as nearly as I could

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:35.920
to make the bird's
head the same size,

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:37.270
so let me just flip it back.

00:18:37.270 --> 00:18:39.480
That's actually better.

00:18:39.480 --> 00:18:41.330
What's the difference
in the information?

00:18:41.330 --> 00:18:43.090
&gt;&gt; The color.

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:44.390
&gt;&gt; Kay Etheridge:
The color's huge.

00:18:44.390 --> 00:18:46.140
Yeah, the color is enormous.

00:18:46.140 --> 00:18:48.100
But also, once you
start trying --

00:18:48.100 --> 00:18:49.510
if you scale it to
the bird's head,

00:18:49.510 --> 00:18:52.410
you notice the tail's not long
enough in the finished plates.

00:18:52.410 --> 00:18:55.310
So sometimes you run out
of space on our plate

00:18:55.310 --> 00:18:59.310
or you woodblock or your page,
even if it's a folio size.

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:00.790
Sometimes you just run out.

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:02.940
So there's more information
in the color.

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:06.020
But if you want to print it
and sell it to a lot of people,

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:11.580
obviously you can't hand-copy
this at any cost-effective rate.

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:13.550
So the printing -- you
lose some information,

00:19:13.550 --> 00:19:17.960
but you also can
disseminate it more widely.

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:23.730
Okay. So here's a famous
animal encyclopedia by a Swiss,

00:19:23.730 --> 00:19:27.500
Conrad Gesner, and who's
our star over here.

00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:30.880
Well, we've seen him before.

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:32.180
That's Belon's [inaudible].

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:33.480
It's oriented differently.

00:19:33.480 --> 00:19:35.100
He credits Belon for this.

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:39.250
So this information that was
collected is now in an image

00:19:39.250 --> 00:19:41.290
that more people can see
in this encyclopedia.

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:44.560
And guess who's also back
in this encyclopedia?

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:47.390
Yeah. So sometimes you
can tell -- notice the --

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:50.950
isn't he facing the
opposite direction there?

00:19:50.950 --> 00:19:52.510
Yeah. So when you
copy something,

00:19:52.510 --> 00:19:54.100
and then it's printed, it flips.

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:57.270
So you can sort of watch these
things flip back and forth

00:19:57.270 --> 00:20:00.320
which is fun, and it's not
identical to [inaudible] print,

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:01.720
but it's pretty close.

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:04.150
There's actually a
mistake in the toe position

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:05.630
of the chameleon in this one,

00:20:05.630 --> 00:20:08.510
but only a herpetologist
like me would notice.

00:20:08.510 --> 00:20:11.690
So Gesner did something
really interesting.

00:20:11.690 --> 00:20:15.480
He did not just compile
other people's information.

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:18.000
He look at mythical salamanders.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.240
Now this is our salamanders,
not snake-like,

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:22.270
but it's hairy, which is weird.

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:29.140
And then he had his artists
draw a European fire salamander,

00:20:29.140 --> 00:20:32.920
they're called fire
salamanders, from a specimen.

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:35.250
And just for fun, there's
what they look like.

00:20:35.250 --> 00:20:38.690
Little snub-nosed
things, color pattern.

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:42.910
And if you look up close at
those dots on the back --

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:49.580
-- those are poison glands.

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:52.020
So the beast theory
wasn't entirely wrong.

00:20:52.020 --> 00:20:55.180
You wouldn't kill an adult human
with the poison from these,

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:56.700
but this protects them
against predators.

00:20:56.700 --> 00:20:58.490
They are poisonous.

00:20:58.490 --> 00:21:01.230
So what's the story with
them surviving fire?

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:04.520
Well, they hibernate in rotting
logs and under the bark of logs.

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:08.080
So the peasant brings the wood
in, throws it on the fire.

00:21:08.080 --> 00:21:10.920
Salamander thaws out and
does I am out of here.

00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:13.470
Goes, you know, running
out of the fire.

00:21:13.470 --> 00:21:15.750
And they think, oh, they
sprang from the fire.

00:21:15.750 --> 00:21:18.960
So there's -- some of these
stories and myths have more

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.850
to them than you might imagine.

00:21:20.850 --> 00:21:24.670
So, jumping forward
another hundred years.

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:26.940
This is our protagonist.

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:31.260
Pretty pearl earrings and
very lady-like, but she ends

00:21:31.260 --> 00:21:36.660
up at some point going
through the jungle of Suriname

00:21:36.660 --> 00:21:40.990
in South America and making
pictures of bird-eating spiders.

00:21:40.990 --> 00:21:42.920
So she was quite intrepid.

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:47.020
But more than that, she
studied the life cycles of moths

00:21:47.020 --> 00:21:49.760
and butterflies on
the post plants

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:52.270
of the moths and butterflies.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:55.990
And this is where I
want to make the point

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:59.450
that she changed how
we viewed nature.

00:21:59.450 --> 00:22:03.230
She put plants and animals
together before anybody did

00:22:03.230 --> 00:22:06.040
in a way that was
ecologically relevant,

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:07.720
not just to be decorative,

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:11.460
but that species
does eat that plant.

00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:14.400
So that's the story I
want to focus on now.

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:17.740
So she was born into a
publishing and printing family.

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:19.080
I'll come back to
them in a minute.

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:21.350
But her father died when
she was about three,

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:24.790
and her mother remarried
this guy, Jacob Marrel,

00:22:24.790 --> 00:22:28.920
who was a very good still-life
painter and included insects.

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:31.440
There's a butterfly
up there somewhere.

00:22:31.440 --> 00:22:33.620
But he also did portraits
of tulips

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:34.960
for people who collected tulips.

00:22:34.960 --> 00:22:37.590
And he decorated these
with little insects.

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:40.520
And as far as I can tell,
he's the only tulip painter

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:43.380
who made these tulip
portraits that put in insects

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:47.190
and he shows them
eating the plant leaves.

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:48.800
Most people wanted
their tulip portraits

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:51.100
to be perfect, not damaged.

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:52.900
And he trained her.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:55.740
And I think she was
very influenced by him.

00:22:55.740 --> 00:22:59.760
But the family firm --
these are her stepbrothers.

00:22:59.760 --> 00:23:05.400
And they published this
encyclopedia of insects.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:08.050
And the interest thing about
this is she would have grown

00:23:08.050 --> 00:23:11.180
up with this stuff in
the house probably.

00:23:11.180 --> 00:23:14.850
This is a plate that's many,
many pages before this plate,

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:16.150
so the adults are here.

00:23:16.150 --> 00:23:18.580
Many, many pages later
are the caterpillars.

00:23:18.580 --> 00:23:21.510
And there's no association
made between them

00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:23.490
and there's no food plants.

00:23:23.490 --> 00:23:25.480
It's just specimens on a page.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:26.780
And they're categorizing them

00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:29.280
by whether the caterpillars
are furry or not furry.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:31.450
So they're trying to
understand all of this nature,

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:34.580
but they're not putting
it in any natural context.

00:23:34.580 --> 00:23:37.810
They're not putting it
in an ecological context.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:40.450
And that's where
Merian comes along.

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:44.550
She had one person before her
who looked at the life cycles

00:23:44.550 --> 00:23:48.770
of these, and put the
caterpillars and adults together

00:23:48.770 --> 00:23:51.400
and the pupae, and this
was Johannes Goedaert,

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:55.230
a Dutchman who published
his book a little more

00:23:55.230 --> 00:23:57.770
than a decade before
she published hers.

00:23:57.770 --> 00:23:59.070
And she read it.

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:00.370
She knew his work.

00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:01.840
But notice, no plants.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:04.780
And sometimes not even
the full lifecycle.

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:07.560
He wasn't as successful as she
was at raising them all the way

00:24:07.560 --> 00:24:08.860
through the lifecycle.

00:24:08.860 --> 00:24:11.020
But still good work,
very good work.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:13.070
She comes along and at the age

00:24:13.070 --> 00:24:16.470
of 32 publishes what she calls
her first caterpillar book,

00:24:16.470 --> 00:24:19.320
<i>Raupen </i>, German
for caterpillar.

00:24:19.320 --> 00:24:20.850
And that's the frontispiece.

00:24:20.850 --> 00:24:22.150
And she publishes two more

00:24:22.150 --> 00:24:24.270
in her lifetime plus
a third tropical book

00:24:24.270 --> 00:24:25.570
which we'll get to.

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:28.360
She studied insects for --

00:24:28.360 --> 00:24:31.350
we know she started when she
was 13, she wrote it herself,

00:24:31.350 --> 00:24:33.430
and probably until
she died at 70.

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:36.200
So for more than five
decades she studied insects.

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:38.850
More than 300 species
of insects.

00:24:38.850 --> 00:24:41.040
But she's best know
today for being an artist

00:24:41.040 --> 00:24:43.910
because she produced these
beautiful compositions.

00:24:43.910 --> 00:24:47.380
So here we've got
one that's colored,

00:24:47.380 --> 00:24:51.630
and here we've got
the etching engraving.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.100
She was taught to make
prints, so in her books,

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:58.790
all of these books, she did --
she raised all of the insects,

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:04.070
she painted them, she engraved
the plates and/or etched.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:06.860
I need to talk to some
expert about that.

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:10.400
And she wrote the text
and she marketed them.

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:13.490
She had a lot of control
over the process which led

00:25:13.490 --> 00:25:15.290
to interesting output.

00:25:15.290 --> 00:25:21.620
So just to show you in terms of
information, here is Goedaert

00:25:21.620 --> 00:25:24.900
and the same species by Merian.

00:25:24.900 --> 00:25:29.190
So that caterpillar
eats that plant.

00:25:29.190 --> 00:25:34.950
And she has not only the
pupae, but she has the eggs.

00:25:34.950 --> 00:25:37.710
And Goedaert's still talking
about spontaneous generation

00:25:37.710 --> 00:25:39.800
of insects in his book.

00:25:39.800 --> 00:25:42.970
He says, they're born
on the wind in one case.

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:44.300
He talks about eggs sometimes,

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:45.980
so he's not even
internally consistent.

00:25:45.980 --> 00:25:49.560
But he didn't quite believe
that all of them came from eggs.

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:50.860
And she did.

00:25:50.860 --> 00:25:52.210
She studied it very explicitly.

00:25:52.210 --> 00:25:56.050
Then if you color the images
you add a lot of information.

00:25:56.050 --> 00:25:59.190
And you add dramatic impact.

00:25:59.190 --> 00:26:00.950
So if you have a wealthy buyer

00:26:00.950 --> 00:26:04.000
and you can sell a colored
copy, more power to you.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.860
Now this is the same species.

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:10.450
Look at his caterpillar
up there, her caterpillar,

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:12.580
and this is the actual
caterpillar.

00:26:12.580 --> 00:26:14.890
Now it's hard when
you're rendering this

00:26:14.890 --> 00:26:17.690
to show those long thin
light-color bristles.

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:20.030
That's really hard to convey,
so the bristles look shorter.

00:26:20.030 --> 00:26:24.000
But other than that
it's very identifiable.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:25.890
Okay. So how to you
make an image like this?

00:26:25.890 --> 00:26:27.900
Well, first you have
to find the animal.

00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:29.920
So where is it?

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.130
Different species --
where's the caterpillar?

00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:34.250
[ Inaudible Speakers ]

00:26:34.250 --> 00:26:36.170
You guys have a good eye.

00:26:36.170 --> 00:26:39.030
Oop, my thing got moved.

00:26:39.030 --> 00:26:43.310
It's a little to the left
of the circle [laughter].

00:26:43.310 --> 00:26:46.920
I went to the 16-9 format
and didn't adjust for that.

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:48.220
So, anyway.

00:26:48.220 --> 00:26:49.520
But you can see the caterpillar.

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:50.820
So you've got to go
and find these things.

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:53.100
And she'd go out in the
gardens and she'd collect them.

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:55.270
And this is the best
stage to start.

00:26:55.270 --> 00:26:57.150
Finding eggs is next
to impossible.

00:26:57.150 --> 00:26:59.370
Catching the adults -- forget
about it because then you got

00:26:59.370 --> 00:27:00.740
to get them to mate
and lay the eggs.

00:27:00.740 --> 00:27:02.360
So you start with
the caterpillar.

00:27:02.360 --> 00:27:03.660
Then you bring it back.

00:27:03.660 --> 00:27:07.040
And she used wooden boxes,
but you've got to raise it.

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:08.340
I've looked at papers

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:12.360
where professionals raising
this species only got 25%

00:27:12.360 --> 00:27:14.410
to metamorphose to adults.

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:15.840
And they were working
on one species

00:27:15.840 --> 00:27:18.840
and they had graduate
students and undergraduates

00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:20.700
in a climate-controlled lab.

00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:22.880
It's not easy to do.

00:27:22.880 --> 00:27:24.590
Some months she would
have been having

00:27:24.590 --> 00:27:28.090
to raise 10 different
species at the same time.

00:27:28.090 --> 00:27:32.280
She also -- the year
she published this book,

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:35.480
she had a one-year-old daughter
and an eight-year-old daughter.

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:37.270
And not a lot of domestic help.

00:27:37.270 --> 00:27:40.050
So makes me tired just
thinking about it.

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:43.830
She said that she had to feed
these caterpillars every day.

00:27:43.830 --> 00:27:45.960
They all had to have
specific foods.

00:27:45.960 --> 00:27:47.570
And she wrote in her book that,

00:27:47.570 --> 00:27:49.470
I could hardly give
them enough nettles

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:51.330
so active were they
in their feeding.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:53.880
These things eat more than
their bodyweight a day

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:55.680
in plant material.

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:56.980
I don't know what you weight,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:58.510
but for me that would
be a lot of salad.

00:27:58.510 --> 00:28:01.370
So this is a lot of work.

00:28:01.370 --> 00:28:04.670
And then she has to
stay up and draw them.

00:28:04.670 --> 00:28:09.320
She would sometimes stay up all
night to get this changing stage

00:28:09.320 --> 00:28:13.420
so that she could illustrate
it and, of course, know nothing

00:28:13.420 --> 00:28:16.270
but candles and I
guess little oil lamps.

00:28:16.270 --> 00:28:19.820
And she would show the whole
lifecycle on the plant.

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:23.010
This animal does
indeed eat fennel.

00:28:23.010 --> 00:28:25.550
So how did she make
these images?

00:28:25.550 --> 00:28:26.850
What's the process.

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:28.870
So she -- we have
her study images.

00:28:28.870 --> 00:28:30.460
They're actually in Russia.

00:28:30.460 --> 00:28:32.440
Long story.

00:28:32.440 --> 00:28:34.330
But we don't have
the plant images.

00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:35.630
They've been lost.

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:36.930
We don't know how.

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:39.550
So this is the lifecycle
including some parasites

00:28:39.550 --> 00:28:42.800
of this particular species.

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.670
This is a -- she
would do a painting,

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:49.030
and then she would make
the engraved plate.

00:28:49.030 --> 00:28:51.160
And I have these
oriented the same.

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:52.460
No, these are reversed.

00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:54.980
And then she might
paint the plate

00:28:54.980 --> 00:28:56.440
or she might sell it unpainted.

00:28:56.440 --> 00:28:58.720
So you can see the
information transfer.

00:28:58.720 --> 00:29:00.280
The thing that's
missing, of course,

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:03.070
is the original image
of the plant.

00:29:03.070 --> 00:29:07.560
And the study doesn't
have as many insects.

00:29:07.560 --> 00:29:11.420
She's added -- by the time she
published it, she's decided

00:29:11.420 --> 00:29:14.480
to add another size
of caterpillar

00:29:14.480 --> 00:29:17.540
that she didn't have originally,
and she's added another type

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:19.630
of parasite in the eggs.

00:29:19.630 --> 00:29:21.920
So a lot of information.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:24.330
Now, I just want to put --
hold up, back up there quickly

00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:27.240
so you can compare the
information in his.

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:28.540
Same species.

00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:29.840
All right.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:31.140
So, don't want to
run out of time here.

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:33.250
She's -- in her first
book she had 50 plates;

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:36.570
her second book she had 50
plates and she had the text.

00:29:36.570 --> 00:29:38.030
And the text is amazing.

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:42.000
It's outside the scope of
this study of this talk today,

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.340
but she looked at behavior, she
looked at the effect of climate,

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:49.670
she looked at all sorts of
things about the insects.

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:51.220
But she was a curious woman.

00:29:51.220 --> 00:29:54.080
And when she was living in
Amsterdam later in life,

00:29:54.080 --> 00:29:56.550
she saw collections
of tropical insects

00:29:56.550 --> 00:29:59.900
like these morpho
butterflies -- spectacular.

00:29:59.900 --> 00:30:01.350
There are no European insects

00:30:01.350 --> 00:30:03.790
that come close in
size or color.

00:30:03.790 --> 00:30:07.240
And she said, I want
to go see those.

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:09.240
And I want to learn --
she said, I don't want

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:10.550
to just see the dead specimens.

00:30:10.550 --> 00:30:14.280
I want to learn how they live,
how they grow, what came before.

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:16.450
So at age 52 she and one

00:30:16.450 --> 00:30:19.680
of her grown daughters take
a two-months ship voyage

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.130
to Suriname, Dutch Suriname.

00:30:22.130 --> 00:30:25.920
She stays on various
sugar plantations and goes

00:30:25.920 --> 00:30:28.990
out into the jungle
and the details

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:31.310
of making this book
are another whole talk.

00:30:31.310 --> 00:30:34.940
But she's there two
years and she comes back.

00:30:34.940 --> 00:30:37.010
She makes a fabulous book.

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:40.070
Now, to put it into
context, other people went

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:41.610
to the New World before her.

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:44.170
This is the kind of
images was in the book.

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:46.870
This is a woodblock print
so it's surrounded by text.

00:30:50.300 --> 00:30:53.850
Hans Sloane, whose collection
founded the British Museum,

00:30:53.850 --> 00:30:55.730
was also in Jamaica before her.

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:57.030
He was in Jamaica here.

00:30:57.030 --> 00:31:00.420
He didn't publish his
book until after her book,

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:04.600
but he made images --
animals on one page,

00:31:04.600 --> 00:31:08.190
plants on another page,
never the two shall meet.

00:31:08.190 --> 00:31:10.760
And this is what
Merian produced.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:16.910
Now, in terms of size, this is a
full folio sheet, so it's large.

00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:19.550
If you bought the colored
edition, and it's large,

00:31:19.550 --> 00:31:25.300
and it's this dramatic,
this is like 3D color IMAX

00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:27.720
to the average European
person who's been looking

00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:32.350
at things uncolored,
smaller, and no drama,

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:34.640
no plants and animals together.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:39.600
So she made this book and
this is what made her famous.

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:41.100
So I scaled these.

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:43.500
I don't think I corrected
the size exactly right,

00:31:43.500 --> 00:31:45.620
but on the left is
the European plates.

00:31:45.620 --> 00:31:46.920
They're quarto.

00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:48.220
And then the folio is

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:52.500
on the right shown
more or less to scale.

00:31:52.500 --> 00:31:56.650
Figs, pomegranates,
bananas, pineapple --

00:31:56.650 --> 00:31:58.440
she tried to emphasize a lot

00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:02.380
of the exotic plants
that you could eat.

00:32:02.380 --> 00:32:03.800
But let's move on.

00:32:03.800 --> 00:32:06.030
So what do you do
with this information?

00:32:06.030 --> 00:32:07.730
You can do a couple of things.

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:10.060
You can use it to
classify the world.

00:32:10.060 --> 00:32:12.000
Linnaeus famously
said something like,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:13.900
God creates; Linnaeus
classifies.

00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:17.560
I'm paraphrasing, but
he was not a modest man.

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:23.710
And he published his
<i>Systema Naturae </i>in 1735,

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:28.490
and the binomial system we use
now is put firmly into place.

00:32:28.490 --> 00:32:32.910
But he named a lot of things
based on other people's images.

00:32:32.910 --> 00:32:34.350
Not always did they
have a specimen.

00:32:34.350 --> 00:32:35.650
They often had images.

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:39.000
And if you're trying to
catalog the natural world,

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.730
and understand it, you need
to know what's out there.

00:32:41.730 --> 00:32:46.410
And Merian, among many other
artists and naturalists work fed

00:32:46.410 --> 00:32:48.210
into the -- were
grist for the mill

00:32:48.210 --> 00:32:50.510
of Linnaeus and his followers.

00:32:50.510 --> 00:32:54.640
And they named over 200
species of plants and animals

00:32:54.640 --> 00:32:56.710
and insects just
from Merian alone.

00:32:56.710 --> 00:32:58.730
And that's one of her --

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:02.490
so that's one way you can use
the information in these images.

00:33:02.490 --> 00:33:06.820
But I argue that -- that was
only a minor contribution

00:33:06.820 --> 00:33:08.120
by Merian.

00:33:08.120 --> 00:33:10.610
I think she changed how we
portray the natural world

00:33:10.610 --> 00:33:13.240
because after her,
people like Eleazar Albin

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:17.220
and many others started putting
animals and plants together

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:19.230
in ways that were
ecologically relevant.

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:21.420
So here's one example.

00:33:21.420 --> 00:33:22.830
Here's another.

00:33:22.830 --> 00:33:25.250
George Edwards --
and you can see here,

00:33:25.250 --> 00:33:28.180
this lizard is contemplating
eating this butterfly.

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:29.480
It's harder to see.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:33.350
There's a tiny little ant
there in front of this lizard.

00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:36.190
This lizard's name is
actually named after Merian

00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:39.410
in the scientific name.

00:33:39.410 --> 00:33:43.960
Here is Mark Catesby who came
along afterwards, and his format

00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:45.700
of his book is very
similar to Merian's.

00:33:45.700 --> 00:33:48.600
And here's a butterfly
and a plant.

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:52.510
But Catesby was fantastic
with birds.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:55.800
And so here's an
ivory-billed woodpecker.

00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:58.880
We wouldn't even really know
what these looked like an aux

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:00.820
if we didn't have these
naturalist artists

00:34:00.820 --> 00:34:03.940
because these are
gone, they're extinct.

00:34:03.940 --> 00:34:06.620
So to remind you again,
let's get reference.

00:34:06.620 --> 00:34:08.690
There's Hans Sloane's boa.

00:34:08.690 --> 00:34:10.270
Somebody engraved that for him.

00:34:10.270 --> 00:34:11.760
He didn't do the artwork.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:14.600
There's Merian's little boa.

00:34:14.600 --> 00:34:16.630
Now I want to talk about scale.

00:34:16.630 --> 00:34:19.270
The talk this morning
made me think --

00:34:19.270 --> 00:34:22.060
it reminded me to
talk about scale.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:25.610
Merian, every image
she made of an insect,

00:34:25.610 --> 00:34:27.890
the insect is life-sized.

00:34:27.890 --> 00:34:30.740
So when you're looking
at her book, not here,

00:34:30.740 --> 00:34:33.260
when you're looking at her
book, you could put that species

00:34:33.260 --> 00:34:36.640
of insect up to it, and that's
how big the adult would be.

00:34:36.640 --> 00:34:38.160
The caterpillars
grow, obviously.

00:34:38.160 --> 00:34:40.710
But the adults -- and I have
a friend who's an artist who's

00:34:40.710 --> 00:34:43.060
actually done this, so we know.

00:34:43.060 --> 00:34:45.750
So that sphinx moth on
the page is the size

00:34:45.750 --> 00:34:48.100
of an adult sphinx
moth would be.

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:50.320
The plants -- sometimes
she couldn't get them

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:53.250
to scale right, and that
boa -- the scale is wrong.

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:54.830
They were not her stars.

00:34:54.830 --> 00:34:56.570
Her stars were the insects.

00:34:56.570 --> 00:34:58.550
So you wouldn't see
a boa that much --

00:34:58.550 --> 00:35:03.730
that size next to a caterpillar,
but at least not an adult one.

00:35:03.730 --> 00:35:07.860
So she messed about with the
scale to get it onto a plate.

00:35:07.860 --> 00:35:10.400
But she's trying to convey
a lot of information --

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:13.280
the lifecycle of the
insect, the snake,

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:15.850
a lot of information
in one play.

00:35:15.850 --> 00:35:20.030
And here's Mark Catesby artfully
draping his little bead snake

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:22.890
because he'd seen Merian's work
and he thought, that's great.

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:24.190
It's a great way to go.

00:35:24.190 --> 00:35:25.810
And his pages were
the same size.

00:35:25.810 --> 00:35:27.110
They were large.

00:35:27.110 --> 00:35:28.410
And he hand-colored
his first editions,

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:30.230
or at least most
of them I'd say.

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:34.940
Now, drama and spectacle, that
came out this morning, too.

00:35:34.940 --> 00:35:36.430
So what is more dramatic

00:35:36.430 --> 00:35:40.590
than a caiman tossing an
egg-eating snake that's trying

00:35:40.590 --> 00:35:44.030
to eat its egg while
also protecting a little

00:35:44.030 --> 00:35:45.930
hatching caiman?

00:35:45.930 --> 00:35:48.940
This is maternal care
in a crocodilian.

00:35:48.940 --> 00:35:50.270
They're one of the few reptiles

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:53.480
that actually do defend their
young, and she's documented this

00:35:53.480 --> 00:35:56.660
in quite a dramatic
and baroque way.

00:35:56.660 --> 00:35:59.960
But these things to
happen in nature.

00:35:59.960 --> 00:36:02.600
So the drama I think
is just as important.

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:05.870
So you've got the ecological
composition with animals

00:36:05.870 --> 00:36:07.170
and plants that occur together.

00:36:07.170 --> 00:36:08.470
But then you've got drama.

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:10.180
You're drawing in your viewer.

00:36:10.180 --> 00:36:12.390
Your viewer is seeing
this tree frog

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:14.880
as eyeing the spider for lunch.

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:18.120
It's seeing this nasty
looking viper rearing

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:22.250
up in a most improbably
anatomical way,

00:36:22.250 --> 00:36:26.320
about to go after this
poor little salamander.

00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:28.350
And then you've got drama.

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:33.790
So this is my favorite plate
in Merian's Suriname volume.

00:36:33.790 --> 00:36:37.360
You've got three
species of spider.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:39.020
You've got army ants.

00:36:39.020 --> 00:36:40.440
You've got leaf cutter ants.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:42.070
You've got a roach.

00:36:42.070 --> 00:36:45.750
You've got a dying
hummingbird and its eggs.

00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:47.860
And you've got a guava tree,

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:51.660
which she says the leaf cutter
ants can defoliate overnight

00:36:51.660 --> 00:36:54.700
down to something like a
broom handle, and they can.

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:58.320
I've been in Costa Rica
and seen it happen.

00:36:58.320 --> 00:37:02.740
She shows the army ants
attacking this roach.

00:37:02.740 --> 00:37:10.030
She shows this spider snacking
on an ant while multitasking

00:37:10.030 --> 00:37:12.380
and guard its egg sac.

00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:16.160
And this bridge of army ant
bodies which actually happens.

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:17.600
This is a screenshot of --

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:20.670
from YouTube of army ants
making a body with their --

00:37:20.670 --> 00:37:22.050
a bridge with their bodies.

00:37:22.050 --> 00:37:24.450
So there's a lot going
on in this image.

00:37:24.450 --> 00:37:27.050
A lot of drama, a
lot of ecology,

00:37:27.050 --> 00:37:30.480
a lot of food chains,
a lot of action.

00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:33.070
Her images, like others',
other people's images,

00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:35.530
get appropriated and
end u in catalogs or --

00:37:35.530 --> 00:37:39.060
excuse me, this is a
children's encyclopedia.

00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:42.150
This is what you and your
kids look in at night.

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:45.640
This is -- yeah, this is one --
actually this series was owned

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:51.060
by Darwin, so you've got spiders
eating birds copied from that.

00:37:51.060 --> 00:37:55.290
This is 170 years
after Merian published

00:37:55.290 --> 00:37:56.750
and it's still going on.

00:37:56.750 --> 00:37:59.370
And now the mate's
coming in to defend it.

00:37:59.370 --> 00:38:03.640
And all of this leads us to
people like John James Audubon.

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:05.720
And so today you could turn

00:38:05.720 --> 00:38:08.510
on the <i>Discovery Channel</i>
or <i>Animal Planet </i>,

00:38:08.510 --> 00:38:11.050
or you can look at an
Audubon print, and, of course,

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:12.500
things are interacting
and, of course,

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:14.150
there are these interactions.

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:16.250
But Merian was the first.

00:38:16.250 --> 00:38:18.070
I'm not saying somebody else
wouldn't have come along

00:38:18.070 --> 00:38:20.420
